  "tutorial/security/simple-oauth2::section-0002": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/security/simple-oauth2::section-0002",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/security/simple-oauth2::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Get the username and password",
    "anchor_id": "get-the-username-and-password",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/security/simple-oauth2/#get-the-username-and-password",
    "section_text": "We are going to use FastAPI security utilities to get the username and password .\n\nOAuth2 specifies that when using the \"password flow\" (that we are using) the client/user must send a username and password fields as form data.\n\nAnd the spec says that the fields have to be named like that. So user-name or email wouldn't work.\n\nBut don't worry, you can show it as you wish to your final users in the frontend.\n\nAnd your database models can use any other names you want.\n\nBut for the login path operation , we need to use these names to be compatible with the spec (and be able to, for example, use the integrated API documentation system).\n\nThe spec also states that the username and password must be sent as form data (so, no JSON here).",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "username",
      "password",
      "user-name",
      "email"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": []
  },
  "tutorial/security/simple-oauth2::section-0003": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/security/simple-oauth2::section-0003",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/security/simple-oauth2::section-0002",
    "level": 3,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "scope",
    "anchor_id": "scope",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/security/simple-oauth2/#scope",
    "section_text": "The spec also says that the client can send another form field \" scope \".\n\nThe form field name is scope (in singular), but it is actually a long string with \"scopes\" separated by spaces.\n\nEach \"scope\" is just a string (without spaces).\n\nThey are normally used to declare specific security permissions, for example:\n\n- users:read or users:write are common examples.\n\n- instagram_basic is used by Facebook / Instagram.\n\n- https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive is used by Google.",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "scope",
      "users:read",
      "users:write",
      "instagram_basic",
      "https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": []
  },
